# TEC.ERP Git & Release Workflow

See `docs/19` §8–15, `docs/24_RELEASE_MANAGEMENT.md`, and `docs/25_DEPLOYMENT_GUIDE.md`.

## Approval Gate Before Commit

Every phase ends with a passed Approval Gate before git commit (`docs/19` §8–9, BUILD-005). Gate validates: Business Rules · UI · Backend · Simulation · Database · API · Testing · Documentation · Production Readiness.

## Commit Standards

Each commit must (`docs/19` §13):

- Represent one logical change
- Compile successfully and pass tests
- Use a meaningful message: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:` prefixes

**Only commit when the user explicitly requests it.**

## Pull Request Standards

Every PR includes (`docs/19` §14):

- Objective and implementation summary
- Impacted modules
- Testing evidence and screenshots (if UI changed)
- Documentation alignment status
- Approval Gate status

## Release Flow

Planning → Implementation → Testing → Documentation → Approval Gate → Deployment → Smoke Test → Monitoring → Release Closure (`docs/24` §3).

A release is an institutional decision supported by evidence — not just a deployment.

## Railway Requirements

- Every PR must remain deployable to Railway (`docs/19` §77.1)
- Production validation includes Railway deployment verification
- Review deployment logs after every production deploy
- Environment variables documented and synced — never committed to git (`docs/19` §78, `docs/26`)

## Repository Hygiene

- Always leave the repository in a buildable state (BUILD-006)
- No secrets, credentials, or `.env` files in git
- Migration failures block deployment (`docs/19` §79)
